WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:13.540
Hi, I'm Athanasia Mowinckel, but everyone just calls me M. And today I'd like to talk

00:00:13.540 --> 00:00:20.520
to you about how I made a package and in that process made some friends.

00:00:20.520 --> 00:00:26.440
So to know a little bit about me, I have a background in psychology with a specialization

00:00:26.440 --> 00:00:32.000
in neuroimaging. And in this field, there's quite a lot of us who do a lot of coding,

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:38.959
but we have no formal training in it, so sharing our code is kind of scary. At least for me,

00:00:38.959 --> 00:00:44.400
it was completely out of the question putting my scripts publicly online. I would just share

00:00:44.400 --> 00:00:48.119
them with my closest collaborators.

00:00:48.119 --> 00:00:56.040
Why is it so scary to put your scripts online? Well, you have this idea that other people

00:00:56.040 --> 00:01:01.320
know what they're doing, so when they see your code, they're just going to think it's

00:01:01.320 --> 00:01:07.879
like this sloppy mess that is completely useless, and they're just going to throw all these

00:01:07.879 --> 00:01:14.919
negatives at you. And in the end, the end message will come, and you have no business

00:01:14.919 --> 00:01:19.879
doing what you're doing. And it's terrifying.

00:01:20.839 --> 00:01:26.919
But that kind of changed a little bit over time, and that started when my colleague D-Duck

00:01:26.919 --> 00:01:32.519
approached me and asked me if we could plot brains in ggplot2. So I'm obsessed with ggplot2,

00:01:32.519 --> 00:01:37.639
I plot everything in it if I can. Well, I force myself to plot everything in it no matter

00:01:37.639 --> 00:01:44.839
what. So he had this idea, and he kind of just turned around and made it happen, and

00:01:45.080 --> 00:01:56.599
we had brains in ggplot2. And it was such a cool process to be able to create our stats

00:01:56.599 --> 00:02:02.519
and immediately project them onto areas of the brain in a way that we would put in a

00:02:02.519 --> 00:02:06.919
publication. I hadn't been able to do that in R before, and I thought it's not just our

00:02:06.919 --> 00:02:13.320
labs that needs this. We have international colleagues that we know also could use something

00:02:13.320 --> 00:02:22.839
like this. So maybe this is a time to figure out how to share your code. So D-Duck gave

00:02:22.839 --> 00:02:29.559
me his script, and I turned the script into a function. And I took that one function,

00:02:29.559 --> 00:02:37.880
turned it into many functions in a package, and I shipped the package off to GitHub. And

00:02:37.960 --> 00:02:50.039
I was terrified, excited, but terrified of what people would think. But it turns out

00:02:50.039 --> 00:02:55.880
I didn't have to be. Because people started tweeting about it, like Mara started tweeting

00:02:55.880 --> 00:03:03.160
about it, and other neuroscientists that I respect a lot started tweeting about the package

00:03:03.160 --> 00:03:12.199
being really good, easy to use, giving them pretty plots, and suddenly all this unequivocally

00:03:12.199 --> 00:03:21.399
positive feedback that I'd never gotten in academia before. It was so exciting and thrilling,

00:03:21.399 --> 00:03:27.880
and it was so much fun having made something that was useful. I'd never made anything useful

00:03:27.880 --> 00:03:36.600
before. And it was just so cool. But kind of the next thing that happened was even cooler,

00:03:36.600 --> 00:03:45.000
because people started doing pull requests to our packages. People we didn't know from before,

00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:51.240
and they helped us improve the efficiency of our functions, making sure they passed our command

00:03:51.240 --> 00:03:58.039
checks, adding unit tests. I'd never heard of unit tests, sorry, before that PR came,

00:03:58.039 --> 00:04:04.759
and suddenly I was obsessed about writing unit tests for everything. And this user,

00:04:04.759 --> 00:04:11.240
John from Johns Hopkins, he helped us prepare our package to be included in the neuroconductor,

00:04:11.240 --> 00:04:16.200
which is like a bioconductor for neuroimaging that we didn't even know existed before this.

00:04:17.160 --> 00:04:24.119
And suddenly, we were connected to this network of our developers for neuroimaging that we didn't

00:04:24.119 --> 00:04:33.480
know before, and we have this reciprocal community. And it's so extremely cool. And now,

00:04:33.480 --> 00:04:40.760
I'm not so scared about sharing my code and putting it online. I do it quite often in my blog,

00:04:41.079 --> 00:04:45.239
and in the multitude of packages I've made since that first one.

00:04:47.720 --> 00:04:52.760
It's just nice to connect with people who do and appreciate the same things you do. So,

00:04:53.959 --> 00:04:58.600
make a package, and make some friends.

